          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## What `device_approve` does\n\nIt completes the **browser half** of the OAuth 2.0 **device authorization grant** with Supabase (Google OAuth):\n\n1. **Verifies** the POST body’s `access_token` with `supabase.auth.get_user()` (401 if invalid).\n2. **Reads** JWT `exp` via `_jwt_exp` and computes a refresh expiry (`REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL_SECONDS`, a fixed horizon since Supabase doesn’t return it here).\n3. **Attaches PostgREST auth** (`supabase.postgrest.auth`) so the next DB call runs as that user (for RLS).\n4. **Updates** the `device_codes` row that matches **`user_code`**, **`status == \"pending\"`**, and **`expires_at` still in the future**, setting `status` to `\"approved\"` and storing the Supabase access/refresh tokens, expiry timestamps, and `user_id`.\n\nIf no row matched (wrong code, already used, expired, wrong status), it returns **400**.\n\n## When it’s called and why\n\nFlow is spelled out at the top of `auth.py`:\n\n```1:10:self-hosted-server/auth.py\n\"\"\"OAuth 2.0 Device Authorization Grant backed by Supabase Auth (Google provider).\n\nFlow:\n  1. CLI POSTs /worker/oauth/device/code → we mint a device_code + user_code.\n  2. User opens /device?user_code=... in a browser. A minimal page immediately\n     triggers supabase.auth.signInWithOAuth({provider:\"google\"}), so the only UI\n     the user actually sees is Google's consent screen.\n  3. Supabase redirects to /device/callback. A tiny script picks up the session\n     and POSTs its JWT to /device/approve, which binds it to the user_code.\n  4. The CLI's polling hits /worker/oauth/token and receives the Supabase JWT.\n```\n\nSo **`POST /device/approve` runs in the browser** after OAuth succeeds—specifically from `device_callback.html`, which listens for `SIGNED_IN` / `INITIAL_SESSION` and POSTs `{ user_code, access_token, refresh_token }`:\n\n```29:37:self-hosted-server/templates/device_callback.html\n      const resp = await fetch(\"/device/approve\", {\n        method: \"POST\",\n        headers: { \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\" },\n        body: JSON.stringify({\n          user_code: USER_CODE,\n          access_token: session.access_token,\n          refresh_token: session.refresh_token,\n        }),\n      });\n```\n\n**Purpose:** link “the person who just signed in with Google” to “the CLI’s pending device/user code,” so **`/worker/oauth/token`** can eventually return real tokens to `git-ai` (or whatever is polling). Without this step the CLI stays in `authorization_pending`.",
