          "text": "Here’s a concise read on your `auth.py` diff.\n\n## What changed\n\n1. **`_jwt_exp`** – Decodes the JWT payload (middle segment) and returns the numeric `exp` claim. It does **not** verify the signature; that’s fine here because **`get_user(req.access_token)` runs first**, so Supabase already validated the token.\n\n2. **`ApproveRequest`** – Drops **`expires_at`** from the client payload.\n\n3. **`device_approve`** – Sets **`access_expires_at` from `_jwt_exp(req.access_token)`** instead of `req.expires_at`. Introduces **`now`** and adds **`.gt(\"expires_at\", now.isoformat())`** on the `device_codes` update so only rows whose device flow is **still within TTL** match.\n\n## Does it make sense?\n\n**Yes.** All three pieces fit together:\n\n- **Expiry source** – Storing access expiry from the **JWT `exp`** is more consistent than trusting a browser-supplied integer. Fewer spoofing/mismatch bugs (`expires_at` from JS vs real token lifetime).\n- **Aligned with the client** – `device_callback.html` only POSTs `user_code`, `access_token`, `refresh_token`, so dropping `expires_at` from the model matches what’s actually sent.\n- **`now` + `.gt(\"expires_at\", …)`** – Previously you could theoretically **approve** a row that was **still `\"pending\"`** but **past `expires_at`** (CLI should already hit `invalid_grant`/expiry on polling, but approving would be inconsistent). Restricting the update to **non-expired** pending rows fixes that hole and duplicates the expiry check at bind time.\n\n## Why it matters vs. marginal\n\n| Change | Impact |\n|--------|--------|\n| JWT-derived `access_expires_at` | **Medium** – Correctness + don’t rely on optional/untrusted client field; aligns DB with actual bearer lifetime. |\n| `.gt(\"expires_at\", …)` on update | **Small but worthwhile** – Tightens the contract at approval time; avoids odd states where an expired device session gets “approved” in DB. |\n\n**Minor caveat:** You’re decoding JWT fields **without** signature verify in `_jwt_exp`; that’s only safe because **`get_user` already authenticated** the access token first. Keeping that order matters if anyone later refactors.\n\n**Formatting caveat:** Relying on string comparison `.gt(..., isoformat)` works if Postgres/PostgREST compare `expires_at` as **timestamptz** (or comparable text) consistently with how `expires_at` was inserted in `device_code()` (also `datetime` → `isoformat()` in UTC). If everything stays UTC-aware ISO strings as in `device_code()`, this is normally fine.\n\n**Bottom line:** The diff is coherent, improves trust boundaries slightly, and matches the callback template—worth keeping unless you deliberately want client-driven expiry for some edge API.",
